			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Observation for acquiring Amy Whip<a name="21036"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 12 04 3:47 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>For all who may benefit,
<br />

<br />
I have been to fear 11 times looking for that darn whip. Most of the times you go you are 'incidental' to your raid in regards to target priority. Most raids go for the 'nameds' and specifically the Golems which can drop the pieces for (at least) 4 epics. Once the golems are done. your raid force will usually find an excuse to get the heck outta fear leaving you looking longly at the Amy Warriors in your tracking window and trying desperately (and unsuccessfully) to convince some of the raid force to stay behind and help you dispatch them 'while most of the zone is already depopulated'. 
<br />

<br />
Even if you are on friendly terms with the raid, getting them to single out an Amy Warrior for a CHANCE at  the tentacle drop is pretty difficult. Most of the time, your raid will kill 4-5 just clearing the southern part of the zone (most of the Amy Warriors are wanderers across the bulk of the zone).
<br />

<br />
The first nine raids I went on, we killed on average 5-6 Amy Warriors per trip (never pulling the Temple, only killing incidental Amy Warriors that got &quot;too close&quot; to the raid force). In those nine raids I only ever saw ONE tentacle drop (my luck is fairly attrocious at the best of times, and being in Fear is rarely &quot;the best of times&quot;).
<br />

<br />
The last two raids I attended, I led myself specifically to address bard epic drops. The nameds WERE still priority targets since they have an annoying habit of chain-aggroing and deathtouching (do not mistake this for a harmtouch; dt cycles every 90 seconds or so and automatically kills a member of the raid/group- no resist). Even if you are there SOLELY to kill Amys, the nameds must still be disposed of first.
<br />

<br />
Having done a bit of research and after asking several other bards regarding their experiences, I decided to pull  &quot;The Temple&quot; in the northwest corner of the zone (tip-clear most of the zone prior to pulling temple). Think of the Temple as an anthill full of Amygdalyns and their friends. You poke the anthill &amp; they literally come pouring out. The best technque I have found is to fire up selos and resist songs and simply train the whole mess. Have your most reliable puller haul something out of the train and lead it back to your group/raid for disposal. Have your puller target the casters first (leave Amygdalyns for last). Once the casters are gone, the Amys pose little threat to a bard with even the most basic knowledge of kiting. Repeat pulling singles out of the train until they are all dead.
<br />

<br />
On both of my latter raids I noticed something I find rather significant, though most will agree it may simply be luck-of-the-drop (though I'd find that hard to believe):
<br />

<br />
Raid 1-9-
<br />
Guesstimate about 60 wandering Amy Warriors-1 tentacle whip
<br />
??? temple Amy Warriors- ??? (never pulled them)
<br />

<br />
Raid 10- 
<br />
8 wandering Amy Warriors - 0 tentacle drops.
<br />
7 temple Amy Warriors- 5 tentacle drops
<br />

<br />
Raid 11-
<br />
6 wandering Amy Warriors- 0 tentacle drops
<br />
6 temple Amy Warriors- 4 tentacle drops
<br />

<br />
I do not claim to know for sure, and I would encourage others among you to support or discredit my observations, but it seems to me the Amy Warriors from the Temple drop the whips SIGNIFICANTLY more often than those found wandering throughout the rest of the zone.
<br />

<br />
Take this as a hard-earned observation and use the informantion as you will. I simply present it here as lessons learned that may save some of you a trip or twelve to this lovely vacation spot for the masochistic.
<br />

<br />
Savidge Rhythums
<br />
Quellious
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span></td>
